('Pasar Kue Subuh: The Morning Rhythm',
'Every day, from two until eight in the morning, the tables at Pasar Kue Subuh Blok M are adorned with an array of traditional delicacies. These range from fried pastries and sticky sweets wrapped in banana leaves to neon-coloured steamed cupcakes—treats that often elude precise English translations. Among these are bika Ambon, lapis Surabaya, and sosis Solo, each snack a testament to Indonesia''s diverse cultural tapestry. These delicious treats, commonly known as *jajanan pasar*, are staples at social gatherings throughout the country, gracing events from joyous weddings and birthdays to solemn memorials. Established in the 1960s, Pasar Kue Subuh Blok M has weathered many changes in its surroundings, from the bustling days of Aldiron Plaza to the rejuvenation brought by the MRT''s arrival in 2019. Yet, the market has not been immune to the impacts of the pandemic. Uni, a dedicated vendor who has been part of this bustling scene for seven years, shares how the pandemic has affected her livelihood. "Before, I could sell up to 1000 pieces of each snack within a day. Now, I''d be lucky to sell 300," she confides. Despite the challenges, Uni and her husband continue to offer their selection of *jajanan pasar* from their spot beneath the eastern eaves of Blok M Square mall, their commitment to preserving this beloved tradition unwavering.',
