('ISA Art & Design: The Art of Remembering',
'Deborah''s journey into the art world began at the age of 26 while she was working as a finance lawyer. Her passion for art collecting was ignited when she purchased a Russian painting at an art exhibition in Hong Kong. After relocating to Indonesia in 1991, Deborah officially entered the art scene by opening Christie''s, the first auction house in Indonesia, in 1996. Her experience grew further when she joined Sotheby''s before eventually founding her own venture, ISA Art Gallery, situated in central Jakarta. Deborah''s role as a senior figure in the art industry allows her to influence and shape the art landscape significantly. Her collection is a testament to her diverse interests and commitment to art. Initially drawn to non-conformist Soviet art, Deborah''s tastes evolved to include Vietnamese art during her early years at Christie''s. She acquired pieces by artists such as Le Pho, Mai Thu, and Vu Cao Dam. The post-Soeharto era in Indonesia opened up new opportunities, leading her to explore contemporary Indonesian art. Deborah visited the studios of prominent artists like Agus Suwage, Yunizar, Masriadi, and Rudy Mantovani, and began acquiring works from celebrated contemporary artists such as Arahmaiani, Heri Dono, and Jompet. As the owner of ISA Art Gallery, Deborah is dedicated to discovering emerging talent and continues to expand her collection by acquiring works from young artists. Her gallery''s mission emphasizes the promotion of women artists and those from the Indonesian Diaspora, reflecting her personal connection as part of a dual-nationality family. Through her endeavors, Deborah not only enriches her collection but also supports and uplifts the voices of new and diverse artists in the community.',
'https://res.cloudinary.com/dxjm1mdjc/image/upload/v1746947567/ce9070e7-8c3f-49a6-92bf-edfc10adc0f1.png',
NULL,
'42e3a2b7-001b-4ee5-a53c-4a7fe140893f'),

('Ruci Artspace: Lighting Up the Local Art',
'Located in the bustling district of Senopati, Ruci Art Space has carved out a niche for itself as a sanctuary of creativity and enlightenment. Derived from the Sanskrit word meaning "the source of light," Ruci Art Space aims to illuminate and inspire through the transformative power of art. The gallery showcases captivating artworks by emerging local artists, who draw from their life experiences and cultural heritage to create pieces that challenge the apathy of modern audiences. Among the current exhibitions, Kinez Riza''s work stands out with its immersive installations. "Ontogeny" invites viewers into a dimly lit room where a moving projected image subtly disturbs one''s sense of balance, creating an engaging and disorienting experience. In another installation, "In the woods is perpetual youth," a fragment of forest is recreated in a chilly, dimly lit space with a floor covered in dying leaves. This surprising combination of sensory elements evokes feelings of tranquility and security amidst the darkness. Ruci Art Space not only serves as an entry point for art enthusiasts seeking knowledge but also provides a platform for those looking to engage with thought-provoking artworks. It encourages analytical contemplation over passive consumption, offering an alternative to mindless entertainment. As Jakarta''s art scene continues to develop, Ruci Art Space stands as a guiding light, fostering dialogue and growth within the community.',
